objectives:
This proposal is within the field of human-computer interaction and accessible computing.

Musical participation for children and adults has long been considered beneficial. However, blind and visually impaired people are often at risk of exclusion from musical participation when learning and playing in group settings with their sighted counterparts. One of the main reasons of exclusion is the inherently visual nature of the communication during conducted ensembles. Conductors communicate with musicians through a set of gestures (and its characteristics) that convey tempo, pulse, rhythm, and dynamics. Visually impaired musicians do not have access to the conductor’s gestures, preventing them to fully participate in music ensembles. Ensuring that children and adults can participate alongside sighted peers is a matter of inclusive practice.

Although some solutions have been previously proposed, they required specialized hardware to sense the conductor’s gestures and convey the information to visually impaired musicians through vibrotactile feedback (https://www.humaninstruments.co.uk/haptic-baton). The cost of such systems makes them useless in real-world settings. Moreover, the effectiveness of such approaches on mix-visual abilities ensembles is unclear [1, 2].

In this dissertation, you will investigate the feasibility of using mainstream smartphones to support mix-visual abilities conducted ensembles. Your three main contributions will be: 1) understand the fundamental challenges and current practices of mix-visual abilities conducted ensembles, 2) design and develop a distributed system that is able to sense the conductor’s gestures and convey vibrotactile feedback through mainstream smartphones, and 3) evaluate the proposed solution.

Tasks that you will undertake include:
1) Literature review;
2) Community engagement and requirements gathering (in collaboration with Bengala Mágica and Filarmónica Enarmonia);
3) Design and develop a mobile gesture recognizer;
4) Design and develop a vibrotactile app;
5) Evaluate the proposed solution;
6) Write the master thesis.

In addition to your master thesis, you will advance the state of the art in the field of ubiquitous computing and accessibility and submit a paper to an international conference or journal.

[1] Bajo, J., Sánchez, M. A., Alonso, V., Berjón, R., Fraile, J. A., & Corchado, J. M. (2010). A distributed architecture for facilitating the integration of blind musicians in symphonic orchestras. Expert Systems with Applications, 37(12), 8508–8515. https://doi.org/https://doi.org/10.1016/j.eswa.2010.05.025
[2] Baker, D., Fomukong-Boden, A., & Edwards, S. (2019). ‘Don’t follow them, look at me!’: Contemplating a haptic digital prototype to bridge the conductor and visually impaired performer. Music Education Research, 21(3), 295–314. https://doi.org/10.1080/14613808.2019.1605344

Optimization of urban mobility is today one of the most relevant challenges in urban planning, in order to improve quality of life and reduce of environmental effects. On the other hand, current use of electronic ticketing solutions enables public transport operators to have a significant amount of data regarding traffic patterns and, at the same time, to provide indirect information regarding transport needs of end users. Moreover, public transport operators make available detailed data regarding their networks as Open Data, namely in GTFS format.

The final goal of this project is to develop, in close cooperation with transport operators of the Lisbon area, optimization algorithms based on machine learning which may be able to find optimal traffic flows and traffic prediction models.

The work will comprise the following steps:

1. Review the state of the art regarding traffic optimization techniques and algorithms;
2. Analysis of available GTFS data;
3. Analysis of available traffic pattern data;
4. Test and development of new traffic solutions;
5. Experimental evaluation and tests;
6. Discussion and conclusion.

This proposal is within the field of human-computer interaction, accessibility, and computational linguistics.

Deaf individuals often acquire a sign language as their first language, which is the language they are most fluent and comfortable with. For these individuals, sign language communication is highly desirable. While for spoken languages, a computer system can display written text on the screen for the user; for sign languages, this approach is generally not possible. While updating a text file containing a written language is fairly easy, updating information in a video of sign language requires hiring a fluent signer and re-recording information content. An alternative solution is to provide computer animation of sign language on websites, but the time and resources needed for human animators to carefully produce fluent and understandable motions of a 3D virtual human character are also substantial.

Prior research has investigated how to automate the creation of sign language animation based on a symbolic representation of the message; however, the resulting animations often feel “robotic” as the natural movements of the human body and timing subtleties of gestures are not encoded in the symbolic representation.

In this work, you will automatically identify speed and timing values for each individual word/gesture in a message: is there a prosodic break (a pause) after the word? If so, what is the time duration of this break? What is the variation of signing speed for each particular word in the message (e.g. slowing down at the end of the sentence)? 


Tasks that you will undertake include:
-	T1: Literature review;
-	T2: Get acquainted with the language corpus and annotation;
-	T3: Design speed and timing heuristics based on structural information of the message;
-	T4: Develop the animation algorithm;
-	T5: Evaluate animation quality with Deaf individuals;
-	T6: Write master thesis.

Related references:
Al-Khazraji, Sedeeq, Larwan Berke, Sushant Kafle, Peter Yeung, and Matt Huenerfauth. 2018. “Modeling the Speed and Timing of American Sign Language to Generate Realistic Animations.” ASSETS 2018 - Proceedings of the 20th International ACM SIGACCESS Conference on Computers and Accessibility, 259–70. https://doi.org/10.1145/3234695.3236356.

Bragg, Danielle, Oscar Koller, Mary Bellard, Larwan Berke, Patrick Boudreault, Annelies Braffort, Naomi Caselli, et al. 2019. “Sign Language Recognition, Generation, and Translation: An Interdisciplinary Perspective.” In The 21st International ACM SIGACCESS Conference on Computers and Accessibility, 16–31. ASSETS ’19. New York, NY, USA: ACM. https://doi.org/10.1145/3308561.3353774.

