objectives:
This proposal is within the field of human-computer interaction and physical rehabilitation.

Each year, approximately 1 million people suffer a Cerebral Vascular Accident in Europe alone, making stroke on the biggest burdens to health and social care. Demand for stroke rehabilitation exceeds supply, and length of hospital stay is decreasing, which can mean less access to therapists, potentially less recovery, and more burden to the caregiver and family. Clearly, new approaches to deliver rehabilitation are needed to improve health outcomes and promote independent living.

One way of increasing the intensity of exercise therapy is to actively involve caregivers (usually family members) in the rehabilitation process. While there have been numerous solutions proposed for home-based rehabilitation, they are not designed to involve caregivers. Caregivers have the potential to facilitate therapy, promote engagement, and increase adherence to rehabilitation programs.

In this work, you will investigate how caregivers can be involved in home-based rehabilitation programs through a user-centered design process where the needs and expectations of stakeholders – survivors, caregivers, and therapists – need to be taken into account. Following this process, you will develop a home-based platform that delivers personalized stroke rehabilitation programs by enhancing communication with therapist and involving caregivers. You will work in close collaboration with all stakeholders that will help you co-design such solution. 

In addition to your master thesis, you are expected to advance the state of the art in the field of human-computer interaction and submit a paper to an international conference or journal.

Your tasks will include:
1) Literature review;
2) Understand the role of caregivers in the rehabilitation process;
3) Design telerehabilitation platform;
4) Develop platform;
5) Evaluate the solution with stroke survivors, caregivers, and physiotherapists;
6) Write your master thesis.

Relevant references:
Silva, I. S., Guerreiro, J., Rosa, M., Campos, J., Pascoal, A. G., Pinto, S., & Nicolau, H. (2020, April). Investigating the Opportunities for Technologies to Enhance QoL with Stroke Survivors and their Families. In Proceedings of the 2020 CHI Conference on Human Factors in Computing Systems (pp. 1-11).

Luker, J., Lynch, E., Bernhardsson, S., Bennett, L., & Bernhardt, J. (2015). Stroke survivors' experiences of physical rehabilitation: a systematic review of qualitative studies. Archives of physical medicine and rehabilitation, 96(9), 1698-1708.

