objectives:
One of the most recent advances on computer networks was the emergence of programmable packet switches. A first system prototype was presented in 2013 [1], and the first commercial Ethernet switch based on a programmable ASIC – the Intel/Barefoot Tofino – came to market in 2016 [2]. Programmable switches, and the new high-level languages that appeared to program them (e.g., P4 [3]), promise to bring an unprecedented level of flexibility and innovation to computer networks.

To achieve these goals and thus fully serve today and tomorrow's networks, we argue that a programmable switch should be able to concurrently support multiple networking contexts. The possibility of running multiple network programs on a single device can be groundbreaking for computer networks, similarly to the emergence of hypervisors to general computing -- allowing multiple virtual machines to run on top of a single server was the cornerstone of cloud computing, for instance.

Existing switches [2], however, support only one networking context as they lack virtualization primitives and techniques for ensuring isolation and resource management of different programs. Recent virtualization attempts to run multiple programs on a single physical switch were made, but they either suffered from very poor performance [4] or lacked generality and flexibility [5]. Ideally, a production-level switch virtualization solution should meet these two goals altogether: efficiency and flexibility. 

The goal of this work is to improve upon the state-of-the-art virtualization techniques aiming to meet those two goals. Towards that objective, the student will explore source code merging approaches at the compiler level to enable multiple P4 programs, from different tenants, to run in a single switch, while guaranteeing isolation and acceptable performance. The student will have the opportunity to evaluate her/his work on the latest generation switching hardware: a Barefoot Tofino switch we have in our lab.

The project will be co-advised by Fernando Ramos (Associate Prof. at IST) and Salvatore Signorello (post-doc at FCUL). Theophilus Benson (Assistant Prof. at Brown University), co-author of [5], and Gianni Antichi (Assistant Prof. at QMUL), will act as external collaborators in the project.

[1] P. Bosshart et al., Forwarding Metamorphosis: Fast Programmable Match-Action Processing in Hardware for SDN, SIGCOMM’13;
[2] Barefoot Tofino: World's fastest P4-programmable Ethernet switch ASICs, https://www.barefootnetworks.com/products/brief-tofino/
[3] https://p4.org
[4] D. Hancock and J. V. M., Hyper4: Using p4 to virtualize the programmable data plane, CoNEXT’16;
[5] P. Zheng et al. P4visor: lightweight virtualization and composition primitives for building and testing modular programs. CoNEXT’18;

