Virtualization is today a key component of large data centres and cloud solutions. The management of available hardware resources and the dynamic allocation, update and deletion of virtual compute, network and storage resources is a major challenge of current data centers and DevOps (Development and Operations) teams.

Infrastructure as Code (IaC) solutions enable to specify virtual architectures using machine readable definition files, providing a way for automatic provision of resources according to the initial and dynamic run time requirements of a given application. Several tools exist for this purpose including, among others, Terraform, Ansible, SaltStack and many others.

The basis of this thesis is to implement an IaC solution for a Microsoft Windows Server eco-system, on top of an existing Open Stack platform, and to develop automatic algorithms and optimization technologies to perform dynamic infrastructure adaptation based on logged events and real time monitoring of the infrastructure behaviour. In this way, dynamic requirements of the end user application may lead to the dynamic allocation of resources and architecture reconfiguration, if required.

The work will comprise the following steps:

1.	Review the state of the art of IaC solutions;
2.	Survey of existing technologies and tools for IaC, taking into account guest Operating Systems requirements;
3.	Analysis and implementation of a test bed for IaC solutions compatible with a MS Server eco-system;
4.	Development, analysis, and test of new algorithms for Infrastructure adaptation based on available logged events and  data monitoring;
5.	Test and assessment of developed algorithms;
6.	Discussion and conclusion.

